[[file:Interior of Santi Giovanni e Paolo (Venice) - Monumento del doge Pietro Mocenigo - Pietro Lombardo.jpg|thumb|Monument of the Doge [[Pietro Mocenigo]] 1481]] [[File:Stile di pietro lombardo, due putti con scudi, 1500 ca. 01.JPG|thumb|Two [[Putto|Putti]] with shields, [[Victoria and Albert Museum]], 1500]] :''Pietro Lombardo is also the Italian version of the name of the theologian [[Peter Lombard]].'' '''Pietro Lombardo''' (1435–1515) was an [[Italy|Italian]]<ref>[http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/346726/Pietro-Lombardo "Pietro Lombardo."] ''[[Encyclopædia Britannica]]''. Web. 18 Jun. 2011.</ref> [[Renaissance]] [[sculptor]] and [[architect]]; born in [[Carona, Switzerland|Carona]] ([[Ticino]]), he was the father of [[Tullio Lombardo]] and [[Antonio Lombardo (sculptor)|Antonio Lombardo]].
In the late 15th century, Pietro Lombardo sculpted many [[Venice|Venetian]] tombs with the help of his sons. These tombs included those of [[Dante Alighieri]], Doge [[Pasquale Malipiero]] and [[Pietro Mocenigo]]. He was the architect and chief sculptor for the [[Church of Santa Maria dei Miracoli, Venice]] (1481–1489) and of [[San Giobbe]] in Venice. He also depicted saints and the Virgin Mary on the walls of several Catholic churches.
Pietro Lombardo is mentioned in line 27 of ''Canto ''XLV by [[Ezra Pound]] as the first in a list of Italian renaissance artists who Pound admired.
