'''Francisco de Mora''' (c.1553&ndash;1610) was a Spanish Renaissance architect.

Mora was born in [[Cuenca, Spain|Cuenca]], and was an uncle of both the architect [[Juan Gómez de Mora]] and the humanist [[Baltasar Porreño]]. He is considered one of the best representatives of [[Herrerian]] architecture, a style that developed in the last third of the 16th century, although his best work also anticipates the [[Baroque architecture|Baroque]] currents that would dominate 17th-century architecture. He was the designer of the [[Convento de San José (Ávila)|Convento de San José]] ([[Ávila, Spain|Ávila]]) and of the [[Palacio ducal de Lerma]] ([[Lerma, Burgos|Lerma]], [[province of Burgos|Burgos]]), which had a major influence on later religious and secular architecture.  He died in [[Madrid]].

