{{Expand Spanish|date=December 2008|Claudio de Arciniega}} [[File:Catedral de México.jpg|thumb|[[Mexico City Metropolitan Cathedral]]]] '''Claudio de Arciniega''' ({{IPA-es|ˈklauðjo ðe arθiˈnjeɣa}}; c. 1520–1593) was a [[Spain|Spanish]] [[architect]] and [[sculptor]].<ref name="answerscom">{{Cite web |url=http://www.answers.com/topic/claudio-de-arciniega |title=Claudio de Arciniega |accessdate=2008-12-10}}</ref> He designed the [[Mexico City Metropolitan Cathedral]] and possibly the [[Puebla Cathedral]].<ref name="answerscom" />
Arciniega was born in [[Burgos]], Spain around 1520 and moved to the [[New World]] in the mid-16th century.<ref name="arquitectuba">{{Cite web |url=http://www.arquitectuba.com.ar/arquitectos/claudio-de-arciniega-biografia-y-obras/ |title=Claudio de Arciniega, Biografía y Obras |accessdate=2008-12-10}}</ref> While in Spain, he worked as a sculptor in [[Madrid]] and [[Alcalá de Henares]].<ref name="arquitectuba" /> After moving to what is now [[Mexico]], he worked on different architectural projects, including building a [[viceroy]]'s palace from the remains of [[Moctezuma II|Montezuma]]'s home and designing the first building for [[Mexico City]]'s university.<ref name="arquitectuba" /> He worked on the Mexico City Cathedral until his death.
