[[File:Dom Michel Felibien 001.jpg|thumb|right||180px|Bullant pavilion at the [[Tuileries]]]]
[[File:Château de Chenonceau - west facade over Cher (4 May 2006).JPG|thumb|right|180px|Bullant's ''Galerie'' over [[Philibert Delorme]]'s bridge at [[Chenonceaux]]]]

{{See also|Antoine Bullant|l1=Jean Bullant (composer)}}

'''Jean Bullant''' (1515 &ndash; 13 October 1578) was a [[France|French]] [[architect]] and [[sculpture|sculptor]] who built the tombs of [[Anne de Montmorency]], Grand Connétable of France, [[Henry II of France|Henri II]], and [[Catherine de' Medici]]. He also worked on the [[Tuileries]], the [[Louvre]], and the [[Château d'Écouen]]. Bullant was a [[Huguenot]].

==Career==
On his return in 1537 from study in Rome, Bullant worked for Montmorency, for whom he transformed the [[Château d'Écouen]] about 1550, built the  "petit château" at [[Château de Chantilly|Chantilly]], and modernised the Château de Fère-en-Tardenois, with its splendid bridge.

He took up the ongoing works at the [[Tuileries]] upon the death of [[Philibert Delorme]] (1570), and was appointed royal architect, (1571–78). At [[Château de Chenonceaux|Chenonceaux]] he built the gallery that spans the river on arches (1576–1577). For [[Catherine de Médicis]] he built the [[Hôtel de Soissons]], (1572–84; demolished in 1748), of which only the ''[[Medicis column]]'' remains.

His treatise on architecture, ''La Règle générale d'architecture sur les cinq manières de colonnes'', was published at Paris, 1564 and 1568. Bullant was also the author of treatises linking theory to practice, on geometry for craftsmen (''Petit Traicté de géometrie et horlogiographie pratique'', 1564), and horology, notably quadrants and solar clocks (''Recueil d'Horlogiographie'', 1561).

