[[File:Güstrow Schloss vom Park.jpg|thumb|[[Güstrow Castle]] designed by Franciscus Pahr]]
'''Franciscus Pahr''' (died 1580) was an Italian architect{{sfn|Campbell|2009|p=37}} who worked in [[Silesia]] and [[Sweden]] from the 1550s. He is remembered above all for his work in [[Uppsala]] where he contributed to the [[Uppsala Cathedral|cathedral]] and [[Uppsala Castle|castle]].<ref name=hs>[http://www.historiesajten.se/visainfo.asp?id=600 "Franciscus Pahr"], Historiesajten. {{sv icon}} Retrieved 3 October 2013.</ref> He refurbished the Upsala castle completely after the fire of 1572. Pahr was from a family of architects who worked in Germany and Sweden during the later part of 16th century and were instrumental in introducing [[Renaissance architecture]] to northern Europe. One of the first projects in this genre in Germany was Pahr's work at Uppsala.<ref name=Pahr>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ne.se/sok?q=Franciscus|title= Pahr|accessdate=5 October 2013|language=Swedish|publisher=National Encyclopedia}}</ref>

==Biography==
Pahr was almost certainly the son of master builder Jacob Pahr from Milan and the brother of Johan Baptista Pahr, Christoffer Pahr and Dominicus Pahr. Pahr was described to have "come from Milan via Brieg, Güstrow and Rostock".{{sfn|Ehrensvärd|2006|p=187}} The Pahr family brought Italian and German [[Renaissance architecture]] to Sweden. In the 1550s, together with his father and Dominicus, Pahr contributed to building the Silesian [[Brzeg Castle]] of [[Brzeg]] and supervised the construction of fortifications at [[Rostock]] and [[Schwerin]]. He probably also built the Castle of Löwenberg (now [[Lwówek Śląski]]).<ref name=ra>[http://www.nad.riksarkivet.se/SBL/Presentation.aspx?id=7939 "Franciscus Pahr"], Riksarkivet. {{sv icon}} Retrieved 3 October 2013.</ref>

In 1558, he entered into an agreement with [[Ulrich III of Mecklenburg-Güstrow|Duke Ulrich of Mecklenburg-Güstrow]] to build a castle in [[Güstrow]],{{sfn|Hahr|1938|p=30}} which he supervised until 1565. He used brick as the main building material.<ref name=ra/>

In 1572, [[King Johan III]] of Sweden invited Pahr and his older brother Domenicus Pahr (''de Pari''), to build the Upsala castle. After the castle's fire, Pahr was retained to rebuild it as Domenicus had become sick; he oversaw the rebuilding process in 1572.<ref name="Hahr1938">{{cite book|author=August Hahr|title=Architecture in Sweden: a survey of Swedish architecture throughout the ages and up to the present day|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=Lqgy2bAXAh0C|year=1938|publisher=Printed by A. Bonniers Boktryckeri|page=30}}</ref><ref name="Ehrensvärd2006">{{cite book|author=Ulla Ehrensvärd|title=The history of the Nordic map: from myths to reality|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=oosYAQAAMAAJ|year=2006|publisher=John Nurminen Foundation|isbn=978-952-9745-20-3|page=187}}</ref> The garden plan for this castle was also designed by Pahr.<ref name="Campbell2009">{{cite book|author=Gordon Campbell|title=The Grove Encyclopedia of Northern Renaissance Art|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=0tlHAQAAIAAJ|date=19 October 2009|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-533466-1|page=37}}</ref> In 1573, he took over the building of the new [[Stockholm Palace]] after [[Anders Larsson Målare]] became ill. In 1578, he supervised work on the restoration of [[Uppsala Cathedral]] which had also been damaged by the 1572 fire, reconstructing the towers in the Renaissance style. In August 1580, Pahr died before completing this assignment.<ref name=hs/><ref name=ra/>

His son, Dominicus Pahr, was a German architect.{{sfn|Wikland|1962|p=192}}

