{{ Italy-architect-stub }}

[[Image:Delorme.jpg|thumb|upright|Engraved portrait of Philibert de l'Orme, c. 1626]] '''Philibert de l'Orme''' ({{IPA-fr|filibɛːʁ dəlɔʁm|pron}}) (3–9 June 1514 &ndash; 8 January 1570) was a [[France|French]] [[architect]] and writer,<ref>Hoffmann 1996; Pérouse de Montclos 2000, p. 19.</ref> and one of the great masters of the [[French Renaissance]].<ref>Blunt 1958, p. xiii.</ref> His surname is also written '''De l'Orme''', '''de L'Orme''', or '''Delorme'''.
==Biography== He was born in [[Lyon]], the son of Jean de L'Orme, a master mason.<ref>Hoffmann 1996; Potié 1996, p. 23 ("Il semble probable que cette stratégie d'ascension sociale ait été préparée de longue date par Jean de L'Orme qui savait que seule la hiérarchie ecclésiastique permettrait à un fils de maître-maçon d'espérer conquérir un statut plus enviable."). Jean is the modern spelling of Jehan.</ref> At an early age Philibert was sent to [[Italy]] to study (1533&ndash;1536) and was employed there by [[Pope Paul III]]. Returning to France he was patronized by [[Cardinal du Bellay]] at Lyon, and was sent by him about 1540 to [[Paris]], where he began the [[Saint-Maur-des-Fossés|Chateau de St Maur-des-Fossés]], and enjoyed royal favour; in 1545 he was made architect to [[Francis I of France]] and given the charge of works in [[Brittany]]. [[Image:Israel SilvestrePartieStGermain.jpg|thumb|left|350px|[[Israel Silvestre]]'s view of the uppermost terrace of the Château Neuf at Meudon shows (with artistic license) its neglected state a century later.]] In 1548, [[Henry II of France|Henry II]] gave him the supervision of [[Chateau Fontainebleau|Fontainebleau]], [[Saint-Germain-en-Laye]]&mdash;where he built the Château Neuf (''illustration, left'') &mdash; and the other royal buildings; but on the King's death (1559) Philibert fell into disgrace. Under [[Charles IX of France|Charles IX]], however, he returned to favour, and was employed to construct the [[Tuileries]], in collaboration with [[Jean Bullant]]. He died in Paris.
Much of his work has disappeared, but his fame remains. An ardent [[Humanism|humanist]] and student of the antique, he yet vindicated resolutely the French tradition in opposition to Italian tendencies; he was a man of independent mind and a vigorous originality. His masterpiece was the [[Château d'Anet]] (1552&ndash;1559), built for [[Diane de Poitiers]], the plans of which are preserved in [[Jacques I Androuet du Cerceau|Jacques Androuet du Cerceau]]'s ''Plus excellens bastimens de France'', though part of the building alone remains; and his designs for the Tuileries (also given by Androuet du Cerceau), begun by [[Catherine de' Medici]] in 1565, were magnificent. His work is also seen at [[Château de Chenonceau|Chenonceau]] and other famous ''[[château]]x''; and his tomb of Francis I at [[Saint Denis Basilica]] remains a perfect specimen of his art. He wrote two books on architecture: ''Nouvelles inventions pour bien bastir et à petits frais'' (1561) and ''Le premier tome de l'Architecture'' (1567).
[[File:Mende-maison-toit-en-carene.JPG|thumb|250px|de l'Orme is credited with popularizing this roof form now sometimes called a ''de l'Orme roof'']]
